          },
          "pause": true,
          "displayType": "poster",
          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>In a patient with inferior vena cava obstruction, which venous system provides t</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>In a patient with inferior vena cava obstruction, which venous system provides the primary collateral pathway for returning blood from the lower body to the superior vena cava?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Internal thoracic veins</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Incorrect. The internal thoracic veins drain the anterior chest wall and are not the primary collateral route in IVC obstruction. The azygos system, which connects lumbar veins to the SVC, serves this critical bypass function.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Vertebral venous plexus</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Incorrect. Although the vertebral venous plexus can participate in collateral drainage, the azygos venous system is the primary collateral pathway, draining directly into the SVC via the azygos vein arch at T4.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Azygos venous system</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct! The azygos vein arches over the right main bronchus at T4 and drains into the SVC. In IVC obstruction, blood from the lower body is rerouted through the azygos system to reach the heart.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Hepatic portal system</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Incorrect. The hepatic portal system carries blood from the gastrointestinal tract to the liver for processing. It does not provide a direct route to the SVC. The azygos venous system is the key IVC collateral pathway.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "The azygos venous system provides the primary collateral pathway in IVC obstruction. The azygos vein drains posterior intercostal and lumbar veins and empties directly into the SVC."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Correct! The azygos vein connects the lumbar veins below to the SVC above, making it the vital bypass route when IVC flow is obstructed."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
                "enableRetry": true,
