          },
          "pause": true,
          "displayType": "poster",
          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>Which of the following correctly describes the thoracic splanchnic nerves?</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>Which of the following correctly describes the thoracic splanchnic nerves?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>They carry postganglionic sympathetic fibres that have already synapsed in the paravertebral chain</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Incorrect. Unlike most sympathetic pathways, the splanchnic fibres pass through the paravertebral chain without synapsing. They remain preganglionic until they reach the prevertebral ganglia in the abdomen.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>They carry preganglionic sympathetic fibres from the thoracic chain to the abdominal ganglia</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct! The splanchnic nerves arise from T5–T12 of the thoracic sympathetic chain as preganglionic fibres that travel to the prevertebral ganglia in the abdomen, where they finally synapse.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>They carry preganglionic parasympathetic fibres from the vagus nerve</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Incorrect. The splanchnic nerves arise from the thoracic sympathetic chain, not the vagus. The vagus nerve provides parasympathetic supply to thoracic and abdominal viscera through a separate pathway.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>They arise from the cervical sympathetic ganglia and descend into the thorax</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Incorrect. The splanchnic nerves originate from the thoracic sympathetic chain (T5–T12), not the cervical ganglia. The cervical sympathetic ganglia give rise to different structures such as the cardiac nerves.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "The thoracic splanchnic nerves arise from T5–T12 as preganglionic sympathetic fibres. They pass through the paravertebral chain without synapsing, continuing to the abdominal prevertebral ganglia."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Correct! The splanchnic nerves are unique because their preganglionic fibres bypass the paravertebral ganglia, travelling directly to the abdominal prevertebral ganglia for synapsing."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
